{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8febd01d97c8afb6", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tDRL-CLBA: A Clean Label Backdoor Attack for Speech Classification via DDPG\n2\tReinforcement Learning\n3\tYueming Huanga , Wenhan Yaoa , Fen Xiaoa , Xiarun Chenb , Weiping Wenb,∗\n4\ta Xiangtan University, Yuhu District Xiangda Road, Xiangtan, 411100, Hunan, China\n5\tb Peking University, No.5, Summer Palace Road, Haidian District, Beijing, China, Beijing, 100871, Beijing, China\n6\t\n7\tarXiv:2607.01729v1 [cs.AI] 2 Jul 2026\n8\t\n9\tAbstract\n10\tDeep learning models for speech classification are vulnerable to backdoor attacks, where malicious triggers cause misclassification\n11\tat inference time. While sample-specific attacks can bypass many defenses, they often rely on poisoned label attack, making them\n12\tdetectable via manual data defense. In this paper, we propose DRL-CLBA, a novel clean label backdoor attack for speech classification that leverages Deep Deterministic Policy Gradient (DDPG) reinforcement learning. We also utilize deep audio steganography to embed sample-specific triggers into source audio, creating feature-space anchors. The proposed reinforcement learning\n13\tframework effectively optimizes target samples toward trigger-bearing anchor points in the model’s deep latent space, enabling\n14\tlabel-migration-free poisoning of target samples. Experimental results across three datasets and four different DNNs demonstrate\n15\tthat DRL-CLBA achieves a high attack success rate , effectively bypassing some backdoor defenses. The attack demonstrates\n16\tstrong resistance against fine-tuning, pruning, and spectral signature defenses, exposing critical vulnerabilities in speech-controlled\n17\tsystems.\n18\tKeywords:\n19\tBackdoor Attack, Clean Label, DDPG, Reinforcement Learning\n20\t\n21\t1. Introduction\n22\tDeep learning models have been extensively deployed in various voice-based human-computer interaction scenarios, such\n23\tas the speech classification tasks: Keyword Spotting (KWS)\n24\t[1] and Speaker Verification (SV) [2]. To improve generalization performance in real-world environments, practitioners\n25\tfrequently incorporate synthetic noise into training datasets for\n26\tdata augmentation. However, existing research indicates that\n27\tsuch noise can be exploited by adversaries as a potential threat\n28\tvector, specifically for backdoor attacks [3].\n29\tBackdoor attacks are generally categorized into poisoned label and clean label attacks. In the poisoned label paradigm,\n30\tan adversary injects a specific trigger into a subset of benign\n31\ttraining data and modifies their corresponding labels to a target class. This process establishes a strong correlation between the trigger and the target class during the training stage.\n32\tAt the inference stage, the model functions as a backdoored\n33\tmodel, which misclassifies poisoned samples into the target\n34\tclass, while still providing correct predictions for benign inputs.\n35\tGu et al. [4] pioneered this field with BadNets, the first backdoor attack against deep image classification models, which utilized pixel-block patterns as triggers. Subsequent research has\n36\tintroduced diverse trigger patterns [5, 6, 7]. However, as these\n37\ttriggers are typically independent of the underlying sample content, they remain vulnerable to backdoor defenses designed for\n38\ttrigger filtering [8]. Most conventional methods require the\n39\t∗ Corresponding author\n40\t\n41\tsimultaneous manipulation of both samples and labels. This\n42\tallows potential victims to thwart attacks by auditing training\n43\tdatasets to detect label-content inconsistencies or identifying\n44\tlow-level image editing artifacts.\n45\tClean label backdoor attacks represent a more pragmatic and\n46\tstealthy threat, as they maliciously tamper with training samples without altering their ground-truth labels. This class of attack typically begins by introducing perturbations into samples\n47\tof a target class to generate \"poisoned samples.\" These perturbations are designed to shift the poisoned samples’ representations within the feature space of a deep classification model,\n48\taligning them more closely with samples containing a trigger\n49\t(referred to as backdoor samples). Consequently, the model is\n50\tcoerced into learning a semantic similarity between the backdoor samples and the poisoned samples, leading it to misclassify triggered inputs into the target category. Shen et al. proposed CSSBA [9], which utilizes image steganography models for trigger implantation and employs the Projected Gradient Descent (PGD) algorithm to iteratively optimize poisoned\n51\tsamples through feature collision. Similarly, Cai et al. [10]\n52\tattempted to facilitate attacks by weakening the inherent robust features of data samples within a surrogate model, subsequently transferring the attack to the target model. However,\n53\tthese methodologies require access to the full gradient information of the deep classification model, which is often inaccessible to attackers in real-world scenarios. Furthermore, these\n54\tattacks frequently employ fixed-pattern triggers during the inference phase, rendering them susceptible to detection by defensive mechanisms.\n55\t\n56\t\fTo uncover more latent security threats in speech recognition models, this paper proposes a novel attack methodology:\n57\tDeep Deterministic action Gradient-based clean label Backdoor Attack (DRL-CLBA). This approach operates without requiring full gradient access to the target classification model,\n58\tdemonstrating both superior stealth and attack efficacy. In the\n59\tattack phase, we employ advanced audio deep steganography\n60\tto embed triggers into source class audio, generating backdoor images that serve as anchors for feature collisions. The\n61\tuse of steganographic techniques ensures that our triggers are\n62\tsample-specific rather than following a static pattern. Subsequently, an actor-critic network is utilized to optimize the generation of poisoned samples. Specifically, the Actor network\n63\tproduces optimized differentials for poisoned samples based on\n64\tthe current feature collision distance and deep feature representations. Meanwhile, the Critic network employs a reward function to maximize long-term feature collision gains, incorporating label-indistinguishability and semantic consistency rewards\n65\tto achieve a clean label attack.\n66\tThe optimization strategy for these networks is governed\n67\tby the Deep Deterministic action Gradient (DDPG) algorithm,\n68\twhich is a type of reinforcement learning (RL) algorithm. By\n69\tensuring the feature vectors of the optimized poisoned samples\n70\tare nearly identical to those of the backdoor samples, the model\n71\tis compelled to learn the backdoor association. Notably, the adversary is not required to modify the labels of any samples.\n72\tWe summarize our contributions as follows:\n73\t\n74\tClean\n75\tModel\n76\t\n77\tBackdoored\n78\tModel\n79\t\n80\tPredefined Number\n81\tof Backdoors\n82\t\n83\tPoisoning Strategies\n84\t\n85\tTrigger Function\n86\tDesign\n87\t\n88\tBackdoor = 1\n89\t\n90\tOne Target Backdoor\n91\t\n92\tBackdoor > 1\n93\t\n94\tMultiple Backdoor\n95\t\n96\tAttack Effectiveness\n97\tEvaluation\n98\t\n99\tModel Training\n100\tProtocols\n101\tLabel\n102\tShift\n103\tNo\n104\tShift\n105\t\n106\tPoisoning Label\n107\tBackdoor Attacks\n108\tClean Label\n109\tBackdoor Attacks\n110\t\n111\tFigure 1: General backdoor attack algorithm workflow\n112\t\n113\tAs illustrated in Figure ??, a complete backdoor attack implementation typically comprises a series of algorithmic components, including the (1) predefined number of backdoors,\n114\t(2) trigger function design, (3) poisoning strategies, (4) model\n115\ttraining protocols, and (5) attack effectiveness evaluation. The\n116\tattacker first determines the number of backdoors to be implanted, which directly influences the subsequent algorithm design. In the trigger function design, implanting a one target\n117\tbackdoor is common in image classification tasks. For example, triggers can take the form of white pixels [4], rose [13], reflection patterns [14], eyeglasses, or color transformations [15].\n118\tHowever, single-target backdoor attacks can be mitigated by\n119\tbackdoor defense methods such as STRIP [16], model pruning\n120\t[17], and Neural Cleanse [8]; therefore, attackers tend to implant multiple backdoors into the model. The effectiveness of\n121\tmulti-backdoor attacks largely depends on the design of trigger functions that can flexibly control multiple target behaviors. Xue et al. [18] first introduced one-to-N and N-to-one\n122\ttrigger mappings, demonstrating that trigger functions can encode complex activation logic across multiple labels. Subsequent works explored more advanced trigger designs. Doan et\n123\tal. [19] and Salem et al. [20] modeled trigger functions as classconditional generators, enabling adaptive and data-dependent\n124\ttrigger patterns for different targets. Hou et al. [21] further proposed an M-to-N paradigm, allowing multiple triggers to activate multiple target classes. Meanwhile, Li et al. [22] enhanced\n125\tattack diversity by employing heterogeneous triggers in parallel\n126\tor sequential poisoning processes. Overall, these studies show\n127\tthat increasingly flexible and learnable trigger function designs\n128\tare key to achieving scalable and stealthy multi-backdoor attacks. Typically, once the trigger function for a backdoor attack is designed, the attacker carries out a poisoning strategy\n129\tby applying it to clean samples together with the trigger to generate poisoned samples, and then modifies the clean labels to\n130\ttarget labels, forming a poisoned set to contaminate the training\n131\tdataset. However, there also exist alternative poisoning strategies that do not modify the clean labels to target labels, which\n132\tposes a significant challenge for the model to learn the association between the trigger and the target label.\n133\t\n134\t• We propose a clean label , sample-specific backdoor attack\n135\tthat achieves a high attack success rate while effectively\n136\tbypassing conventional backdoor defense mechanisms.\n137\t• We leverage deep steganography to generate backdoor\n138\tspeechs and integrate them with feature collision techniques to produce poisoned samples, ensuring high imperceptibility.\n139\t• The effectiveness of the proposed attack is rigorously validated across multiple datasets and speech classification\n140\tarchitectures.\n141\t2. Background\n142\t2.1. Backdoor Attacks\n143\tThe 360 Vulnerability Research Institute released the Large\n144\tModel Security Vulnerability Report in 2024, highlighting the\n145\trisk of backdoor injection in large language models. The report documents an incident in which Hugging Chat Assistants\n146\twas subjected to a backdoored model replacement, triggering\n147\tinformation exfiltration when users entered email-related inputs\n148\t[11]. A joint micro-poisoning study conducted by institutions\n149\tincluding the UK AI Safety Institute demonstrates that as few\n150\tas 250 malicious documents are sufficient to successfully implant a backdoor into a large model, causing it to generate nonsensical outputs when specific trigger words are provided [12].\n151\tThese reports indicate that studying how backdoor attacks pose\n152\tthreats in real-world scenarios is of significant importance.\n153\t\n154\tClean-label backdoor attacks avoid modifying labels, mak2\n155\t\n156\t\fing them more stealthy but also harder to optimize, especially in\n157\tmulti-backdoor settings. Existing works mainly extend singlebackdoor strategies to support multiple triggers through different optimization mechanisms. First, adversarial optimizationbased methods enable multiple trigger learning without label\n158\tsupervision. Gong et al. [23] and Wang et al. [24] generate optimized triggers via surrogate models, while Xing et al.\n159\t[25] and Yin et al. [26] leverage PGD or generative models to\n160\tlearn diverse trigger patterns, which can be naturally extended\n161\tto multi-trigger scenarios. Second, feature manipulation-based\n162\tmethods enhance trigger effectiveness by weakening clean features or amplifying trigger signals. Zhu et al. [27] and You et\n163\tal. [28] utilize attribute editing to construct multiple semantic\n164\ttriggers, while Xie et al. [29] and Yuan et al. [30] suppress original features in spatial or frequency domains, enabling multiple\n165\ttriggers to coexist with reduced interference. Finally, sample\n166\tselection-based methods focus on poisoning boundary or sensitive samples to improve multi-trigger reliability. Wu et al.\n167\t[31] and Tang et al. [32] identify vulnerable samples near decision boundaries and embed adaptive triggers, while Zhang et al.\n168\t[33] further enhances multi-trigger separability through feature\n169\talignment strategies. Overall, these studies suggest that combining clean-label constraints with diverse trigger generation,\n170\tfeature manipulation, and sample selection strategies provides\n171\ta feasible pathway toward scalable multi-backdoor attacks.\n172\t\n173\tall injected training samples must be correctly labeled according to their semantic content, making the attack difficult to detect through label inspection. Under this constraint, the attacker\n174\taims to implant a backdoor into the model by carefully crafting\n175\tmalicious yet benign-looking samples during training.\n176\tThe primary goal of the attacker is to maximize the attack\n177\tsuccess rate (ASR), defined as the probability that inputs containing the trigger are misclassified into the target class at inference time, while maintaining a high benign accuracy (BA).\n178\tHere, benign accuracy refers to the classification accuracy on\n179\tclean, non-poisoned test images. Preserving BA is essential to\n180\tensure that the backdoored model exhibits normal performance\n181\ton benign data and thus avoids suspicion. In addition, the invisibility of malicious images constitutes a critical requirement in\n182\tthe clean label setting. The perturbations or triggers embedded\n183\tin poisoned samples are designed to be imperceptible to human\n184\tobservers and to remain semantically consistent with the original class, further enhancing the stealthiness of the attack and\n185\treducing the likelihood of detection by manual inspection or\n186\tautomated defense mechanisms.\n187\t3.2. The Pipeline of Proposed Attack.\n188\tFigure 3 illustrates the injection pipeline of our proposed attack, which comprises four primary stages: (1) Initialization\n189\tStep, (2) DRL-CLBA Training, (3) Poisoned Dataset Generation, and (4) Backdoor Implantation. In the first step, we\n190\tinitialize the various neural network architectures required for\n191\treinforcement learning. Simultaneously, an audio steganography model is utilized to generate backdoor samples and their\n192\tcorresponding feature vectors, which serve as anchors for the\n193\tsubsequent optimization. In the second step, we employ a\n194\tDDPG-based reinforcement learning framework to maximize a\n195\tseries of reward functions, specifically focusing on feature collision. This trains the actor network to generate poisoned samples that are precisely feature collisions with the target anchors.\n196\tIn the third step, the optimized poisoned samples are injected\n197\tinto the target training set following the standard protocol for\n198\tpoisoning-based backdoor attacks. Critically, we maintain the\n199\tclean label nature of the attack by preserving the original labels\n200\tof all speech samples. In the last step, the target model undergoes training on the poisoned training dataset, resulting in the\n201\tconvergence of a backdoored model.\n202\t\n203\t2.2. Speech Classification Models\n204\tThis research focuses on speech classifiers. Speech classifiers predict labels based on the speech waveforms or spectrograms. In recent years, deep neural networks (DNNs) have\n205\tachieved optimal efficacy in the domains [1, 34, 35, 36, 37],\n206\thence raising substantial security issues. The classifier Cθ is\n207\tconsistently tuned using the cross-entropy loss as outlined below:\n208\tL(x,y)∈D = arg max p(y | Cθ (x))\n209\tθ\n210\t\n211\t(1)\n212\t\n213\tThe (x, y) represents the model inputs and corresponding true\n214\tlabels. Training on the dataset D enables the classifier to discern the correlations between a particular input feature and the\n215\tpotential attack labels, hence posing a risk of data poisoning\n216\tbackdoor attacks.\n217\t\n218\t3.3. The Principle of Feature Collision\n219\tFigure 2 illustrates the mechanism of the clean label backdoor attack via feature collision. Let the feature extraction\n220\tcomponent of the target DNN model be denoted by the funcK src\n221\ttion h(·). Let the source class sample set be X src = {xis }i=1\n222\tKtar\n223\t. First, the adand the target class sample set be Xtar = {xit }i=1\n224\tversary utilizes a trigger function ξ to construct backdoor samples—specifically, samples embedded with a trigger δtrg , denoted as ξ(xis , δtrg ). The resulting feature vectors extracted by\n225\tsrc\n226\tthe DNN, Htrg\n227\t= {hisrc = h(ξ(xis , δtrg ))}, serve as anchors. Subsequently, the adversary employs a feature collision algorithm\n228\tto optimize a poisoned sample x̂it ← xit . The optimization objective is to minimize the distance between the feature representation of the poisoned sample, h( x̂it ), and a specific anchor\n229\t\n230\t3. Methodology\n231\t3.1. Threat Model\n232\tCommonly, backdoor attacks occur when an adversary conceals a backdoored model behind an API or distributes a compromised model to end-users, thereby facilitating malicious exploitation.\n233\tWe consider a clean label threat model in which the attacker\n234\tis allowed to manipulate the training dataset and influence the\n235\ttraining process, but has no access to modifying the architecture or internal parameters of the target model. In particular,\n236\t3\n237\t\n238\t\fFeature Collision\n239\tPoisoned Samples\n240\tBackdoor Samples\n241\t\n242\terator is defined by the following loss function:\n243\ttrg\n244\t′\n245\t′\n246\tLg (x s , xtrg\n247\ts , δtrg , δtrg ) = ∥x s − x s ∥ + ∥δtrg − δtrg ∥\n248\t\n249\t(2)\n250\t\n251\tThe first term aims to reduce the differences between source audios and backdoor audios, thereby ensuring the imperceptibility\n252\tof the backdoor attack. The second term is to minimizing the\n253\treconstruction error of the trigger audios.\n254\tSource Class\n255\tSamples\n256\t\n257\tTarget Class\n258\tSamples\n259\t\n260\t3.5. DRL-CLBA Training\n261\tThe DRL-CLBA training process is illustrated in Figure 3(2).\n262\tTo address the limitations of gradient based feature collision\n263\toptimization, we reformulate clean label backdoor attacks as a\n264\tsequential decision making process. We guide the generation of\n265\tpoisoned samples through a Markov Decision Process (MDP)\n266\tdefined by the quadruple (S , A, P, R). In this formulation, the\n267\tgradual perturbation of a target class sample, which aimed at\n268\taligning its deep feature representation with a trigger embedded source class samples, is solved using the Deep Deterministic action Gradient (DDPG) algorithm. Next, we formalize the\n269\tstate, reward, action network, and value network in the MDP.\n270\tState, Action, Update. At each decision step t, the classification model acts as an agent observing a state st ∈ S , which\n271\tcaptures the current alignment between the poisoned sample\n272\tand the source-class anchor. To ensure stability and avoid highdimensional raw data issues, the state is constructed using deep\n273\tfeature representations and constraint-related statistics:\n274\t\u0002\n275\t\u0003\n276\tst = h(xt ), h∗s , ∥h(xt ) − h∗s ∥2 , ∥xt − xtar ∥2\n277\t(3)\n278\t\n279\tFigure 2: Feature collisions\n280\t\n281\tsrc\n282\tin Htrg\n283\t. Consequently, the DNN is compelled to learn the following mapping: h(ξ(xis , δtrg )) ≈ h( x̂it ). Thus, the model consequently misidentifies the predicted labels of source-class samples embedded with triggers as highly similar to the optimized\n284\ttarget-class labels in the deep latent space. Based on this property, an attacker can exploit the optimized target-class samples\n285\tto successfully carry out the attack.\n286\tIn the data poisoning stage, the adversary then injects a significant volume of these poisoned samples x̂it into a clean training dataset to execute the poisoning-based backdoor attack.\n287\tDuring the inference phase, the adversary applies the trigger\n288\tto source class samples; the DNN subsequently misclassifies\n289\tthese samples into the target category, signifying a successful\n290\tbackdoor activation.\n291\t\n292\twhere h(xt ) represents the fixed feature extractor’s output for\n293\tthe t step intermediate poisoned sample xt , and h∗s denotes one\n294\tof anchor features of the triggered source class sample. The\n295\txtar denotes a target class sample. This design explicitly accounts for the dual objectives of feature collision and perturbation boundedness. The agent interacts with the environment to\n296\tobtain gradient information that characterizes how the current\n297\tsample should be updated in order to optimize the feature collision distance. Based on this information, the agent applies a\n298\tcontinuous perturbation increment ∆xt to iteratively update the\n299\tpoisoned sample. Specifically, the sample is updated as\n300\t\n301\t3.4. Initialization Step and Deep Steganography\n302\tThe initial stage consists of two primary steps. In the first\n303\tstep, we utilize an audio deep steganography model, referred\n304\tto as the backdoor generator, to produce anchor vectors. In\n305\tthe second step, we initialize the components of the Deep Deterministic action Gradient (DDPG) framework: the Actor network µ(s|θµ ) and the Critic (Value) network Q(s, a|θ Q ). Furthermore, to facilitate the estimation of long-term feature collision\n306\tgains and ensure training stability, we initialize two corresponding target networks, µ′ and Q′ , with identical weights to their\n307\tprimary counterparts.\n308\tThe backdoor generator is designed as an encoder-decoder\n309\tarchitecture based on deep steganography [38], comprising\n310\tthree functional modules: the preparation network, the hiding network, and the reveal network. The preparation network\n311\tencodes the trigger audio into a lower-dimensional representation. The hiding network is an 1D convolutional encoder that\n312\taccepts both the preparation network’s output and the source\n313\tclass audio sample x s as inputs, producing the backdoor sample\n314\txtrg\n315\ts . The reveal network decodes the latent information from\n316\tthe backdoor sample to reconstruct the original trigger audio,\n317\toutputting the predicted trigger δ′trg . By leveraging an encoderdecoder structure with high-density residual connections, the\n318\tgenerator ensures that the steganographic triggers are samplespecific—varying for each backdoor sample rather than following a fixed pattern. The training objective for the backdoor gen-\n319\t\n320\txt+1 = Πϵ (xt + ∆xt ),\n321\t\n322\t(4)\n323\t\n324\twhere Πϵ denotes a projection operator that enforces the constraint |xt+1 − xtar | p ≤ ϵ. This projection ensures that the generated poisoned sample does not deviate excessively from the\n325\tinitial target point. Moreover, this iterative update mechanism\n326\tenables a multi-step optimization process that incorporates historical interaction information, rather than relying on a singlestep update strategy, thereby improving the stability and flexibility of the attack optimization procedure.\n327\tReward. The optimization is governed by a multi-objective\n328\treward function rt designed to balance feature collision, imperceptibility, and semantic consistency. It is defined as:\n329\trt = −λ1 ∥h(xt+1 ) − h∗s ∥2 − λ2 ∥xt+1 − xtar ∥2\n330\t+ λ3 · I[ f (xt+1 ) = ytar ]\n331\t4\n332\t\n333\t(5)\n334\t\n335\t\fActor\n336\tNetwork\n337\tµ (s | θ µ )\n338\t\n339\tTarget Actor\n340\tNetwork\n341\tµ '( s | θ µ ' )\n342\t\n343\tCritic\n344\tNetwork\n345\tQ ( s, a | θ Q )\n346\t\n347\tTarget Critic xanc\n348\tNetwork\n349\t\n350\tQ '( s, a | θ Q ' )\n351\t\n352\tExperience\n353\tReplay Buffer\n354\t\n355\tD\n356\t\n357\tx0 ∈ xtar\n358\t\n359\tst\n360\t\n361\txtar\n362\t\n363\ths*\n364\t\n365\t(1 Initialization Step\n366\t\n367\tst\n368\t\n369\tµ (s | θ µ )\n370\t\n371\tat = ∆xt\n372\t\n373\tUpdate\n374\t\n375\tst ← st +1\n376\t\n377\tθ µ'\n378\t\n379\tUpdate\n380\t\n381\txanc\n382\t\n383\tTrain\n384\tPoisoned\n385\tDataset\n386\t\n387\tBackdoored Model\n388\t\n389\t(3) Poisoned Dataset Generation\n390\t\n391\txt +1\n392\t\n393\tst +1\n394\t\n395\tReward\n396\t\n397\t(4) Backdoor Implantation\n398\t\n399\trt\n400\t\n401\tMini\n402\tBatch\n403\t\n404\tD\n405\t\n406\t( si , ai , ri , si +1 )iM=\n407\t1\n408\t\n409\t∇θ µ\n410\t\n411\tQ − value\n412\t\n413\tQ ( s, a | θ Q )\n414\t\n415\t∇θ Q\n416\t\n417\tQ '− value\n418\t\n419\tQ '( s, a | θ Q ' )\n420\t\n421\tEMA\n422\t\n423\tθ Q'\n424\t\n425\t(2) DRL-CLBA Training\n426\tFigure 3: The DRL-CLBA attack pipeline\n427\t\n428\tBy penalizing the distance to the anchor features and the original target sample while rewarding correct target class predictions ytar , the reward function enables the agent to learn sophisticated attack strategies that are often difficult to optimize using\n429\ttraditional gradient descent.\n430\tAction and Value Network. The attack strategy employs a\n431\tDeep Deterministic Policy Gradient (DDPG) framework. The\n432\taction network µ(s|θµ ) maps the state s to a continuous perturbation ∆xt , perceiving the joint distribution of feature and input\n433\tspaces to drive samples toward the target domain. To evaluate\n434\tthese actions, the value network Q(s, a|θ Q ) estimates the expected cumulative reward, balancing immediate collision gains\n435\twith future potential.To ensure training stability and prevent divergence, the architecture incorporates target networks µ′ and\n436\tQ′ , synchronized through soft updates. Structurally, the value\n437\tnetwork is a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) that fuses state and\n438\taction vectors into a scalar quality assessment, directly guiding\n439\tthe gradient updates for the action network.\n440\tThe DDPG Training Procedure. The training procedure involves a cycle of interaction, sampling, and network refinement. First, the agent interacts with the environment to store\n441\ttransitions (st , at , rt , st+1 ) in a replay buffer D. Subsequently, a\n442\tmini-batch of N samples is drawn to update the networks. The\n443\tvalue network is optimized by minimizing the Mean Squared\n444\tError (MSE) loss between the predicted Q-value and the target\n445\tvalue yi :\n446\t\u00112\n447\t1 X\u0010\n448\tL(θ Q ) =\n449\t(6)\n450\tyi − Q(si , ai |θ Q )\n451\tN i\n452\t\n453\tcurate assessment of the \"quality\" of a perturbation strategy.Simultaneously, the policy network is updated using the\n454\tDeterministic Policy Gradient Theorem, aiming to maximize\n455\tthe expected value as evaluated by the critic. The gradient for\n456\tthe policy parameters θµ is approximated as:\n457\ti\n458\th\n459\t(8)\n460\t∇θµ J ≈ E st ∼D ∇a Q(s, a|θ Q ) s=s ,a=µ(s ) ∇θµ µ(s|θµ ) s=s\n461\tt\n462\t\n463\t′\n464\t\n465\t′\n466\t\n467\tt\n468\t\n469\tFinally, the target networks are updated via an exponential moving average (EMA) with a decay rate τ ≪ 1, ensuring the convergence and stability of the entire optimization process across\n470\titerations. In our method, a multilayer perceptron is used to\n471\timplement the action and value networks.\n472\t3.6. Poisoned Dataset Generation\n473\tOnce the DRL training phase is complete, the optimized policy µ∗ is frozen and deployed as a generator to produce poisoned samples from the target class dataset Xtar . Unlike traditional optimization-based attacks, this generation process is\n474\tan iterative inference procedure that does not require access\n475\tto the model’s gradients. Given an initial target class sample x0 ∈ Xtar , an anchor h∗s is first selected based on the\n476\tnearest neighbor principle. This forms the initial state s0 =\n477\t\u0002\n478\t\u0003\n479\th(x0 ), h∗s , ∥h(x0 ) − h∗s ∥2 , 0 . The poisoned sample is then\n480\tevolved through a sequence of deterministic actions:\n481\txt+1 = Πϵ (xt + µ∗ (st |θµ )),\n482\t\n483\tt = 0, 1, . . . , T\n484\t\n485\t(9)\n486\t\n487\tThis process continues until a maximum number of steps T\n488\tis reached or the feature distance dt falls below a predefined\n489\tthreshold. Notably, the state input for the policy network depends solely on the output of the model’s final feature layer\n490\trather than its internal weight gradients. This significantly\n491\t\n492\twhere the target yi is computed as:\n493\tyi = ri + γQ′ (si+1 , µ′ (si+1 |θµ )|θ Q )\n494\t\n495\tt\n496\t\n497\t(7)\n498\t\n499\tThis loss function ensures that the critic provides an ac5\n500\t\n501\t\frelaxes the requirement for the attacker’s surrogate model to\n502\tmatch the target model’s architecture or parameters, potentially\n503\tenabling clean label attacks in scenarios where only model outputs are accessible.\n504\tThe final output of the inference process is defined as the\n505\tpoisoned sample x poi = xT . Due to the projection operator\n506\tused during iteration, the sample maintains visual consistency\n507\twith the original target label ytar in the pixel space, satisfying\n508\t∥x poi −x0 ∥ p ≤ ϵ.To construct the complete poisoned subset D poi ,\n509\tthe frozen policy µ∗ is applied to a randomly selected portion\n510\tof the target class dataset Xtar governed by the poisoning rate\n511\tNρ\n512\tρ poi . This results in a subset D poi = {(xipoi , yitar )}i=1\n513\t, where Nρ\n514\tdenotes the number of poisoned samples. Crucially, the original labels ytar are preserved throughout this process, ensuring\n515\tthe \"clean label\" nature of the attack, which bypasses manual\n516\tdata inspection.\n517\t\n518\tSV dataset extracted from the AISHELL-3 Mandarin corpus. It\n519\tcomprises 18081 utterances from the 50 speakers with the most\n520\trecordings. For the SER task, we split the English and Chinese\n521\tdatasets of the ESD corpus [43] into two separate sub-datasets.\n522\tThey share the same number of speakers and utterances. Each\n523\tdataset contains 10 speakers with 5 emotional states.\n524\tOur attacks target four DNN models: ERes2Net [44], KWSViT [1], EAT-S [45], and CAM++ [46]. All four models are\n525\tsuitable for speech classification tasks and respectively cover\n526\ttraditional convolutional architectures, advanced self-attention\n527\tmechanisms, as well as their combinations.\n528\t4.2. Baseline Selection.\n529\tFollowing the methodology described in chapter 3.3, we\n530\tadapt existing non-clean label poisoning based single backdoor attacks into clean label attack variants, utilizing the Projected Gradient Descent (PGD) algorithm to optimize the target samples. The adapted methodologies include the Ultra\n531\tmethod [47] and the OneSpec method [48]. Furthermore, this\n532\tstudy extends mature clean label attack frameworks to speech\n533\tclassification models, incorporating the following three advanced approaches: Clean Label Backdoor Attack (CBA) [49],\n534\tClean Label Sample-Specific Backdoor Attack (CSSBA) [9],\n535\tTargeted Universal Adversarial Perturbation Backdoor Attack\n536\t(TUAPBA) [10].\n537\t\n538\t3.7. Backdoor Implantation\n539\tIn the final stage, the attacker merges the poisoned subset\n540\tD poi with the original benign training dataset Dbenign to form\n541\tthe final training dataset Dtrain = Dbenign ∪ D poi . The victim\n542\tmodel is then trained on Dtrain using standard supervised learning procedures. No modifications to the model’s hyperparameters or loss functions are required, as the model updates its\n543\tparameters θ by minimizing the standard cross-entropy loss:\n544\tX\n545\tLce (M(xi ; θ), yi )\n546\t(10)\n547\tmin\n548\tθ\n549\t\n550\t4.3. Evaluation Results and Comparison\n551\tAttack Setup. On three datasets, we set the poisoning rate\n552\tρ poi = 0.8%. For our attack, we use the single frequency audio from the OneSpec as the trigger audio and perform feature\n553\tcollision for 3000 epochs. For the backdoor generator, we use\n554\tthe adam optimizer to fintune 80 epochs on all datasets. The\n555\tinitial learning rate is 0.0002, and the learning rate is divided\n556\tby 0.97 for every 10 epochs.\n557\tAttack Performance. (1) KWS task. Table 1 presents the\n558\texperimental results of clean-label backdoor attacks on three\n559\tKWS datasets across four different deep neural network models. The proposed DRL-CLBA method is compared with five\n560\tbaseline attack methods. The evaluation metrics include ASR\n561\tand BA. On the KWS task, the DRL-CLBA method achieves\n562\taverage ASR values of 88.09%, 89.76%, and 90.12% on the\n563\tSCD, AudioMNIST, and LibriKWS-20 datasets, respectively.\n564\tCompared with single backdoor settings where ASR can easily exceed 98%, these results verify that clean-label attacks\n565\tare significantly more challenging. However, across all three\n566\tdatasets and models, the ASR of the DRL-CLBA method consistently exceeds the maximum ASR achieved by the baseline\n567\tmethods. The differences between the ASR of DRL-CLBA\n568\tand the average ASR of the five baseline methods on the three\n569\tdatasets are 31.62%, 31.11%, and 25.01%, respectively. This\n570\tdemonstrates that, compared with the standard PGD algorithm,\n571\tthe reinforcement-learning-driven poisoned samples proposed\n572\tin this work are more effectively learned by the model as incorrect deep features. From the experimental results, it can\n573\talso be observed that different triggers used as anchor samples\n574\tlead to significantly different outcomes. For example, when using the Ultra method as a trigger, the ASR values on the three\n575\t\n576\t(xi ,yi )∈Dtrain\n577\t\n578\tAlthough the training process itself remains conventional, the\n579\tunderlying data distribution has been strategically manipulated.\n580\tBecause x poi is forced into the feature distribution region of the\n581\tsource category (i.e., h(x poi ) ≈ h∗s ), the model is compelled to\n582\tassociate the source category’s feature space with the target label ytar to achieve minimal training error. This \"feature-level\n583\tmisleading\" creates a latent backdoor vulnerability; while the\n584\tmodel performs normally on clean data, it will misclassify any\n585\tsource-class sample containing the trigger as the target class\n586\tduring deployment.\n587\t4. Experiments and Results\n588\t4.1. Models and Datasets.\n589\tOur experiments were conducted on three different speech\n590\tclassification tasks: keyword spotting (KWS), speaker verification (SV), and speech emotion recognition (SER). For the\n591\tKWS task, we use three different KWS datasets, including SCD\n592\t[39], AudioMNIST [40], and LibriKWS-20 [41]. The first two\n593\tdatasets contain 35 and 10 classes of commands, respectively.\n594\tLibriKWS-20 is a subset of the evaluation split of the LibriSpeech dataset and consists of 20 classes. For the SV task,\n595\twe use the AISHELL3-50 and VoxCeleb1-50 [42] datasets.\n596\tVoxCeleb1-50 is a SV dataset derived from the large-scale VoxCeleb1 corpus, which was collected from YouTube videos. It\n597\tcontains 18354 utterances from the top 50 most talkative speakers selected from the VoxCeleb1-H subset. AISHELL3-50 is a\n598\t6\n599\t\n600\t\fTable 1: Attack performance on t